value.value: Painful sensation in the chest wall region.
An abnormal communication between the large intestine and another organ or cavity.

label.value: Stage II Renal Cell Cancer AJCC v6

value.value: Stage II includes: T2, N0, M0.  T2: Tumor more than 7 cm in greatest dimension limited to the kidney.  N0: No regional lymph node metastases.  M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th Ed.)
Bleeding originating from the colon.
Blockage of the normal flow of the intestinal contents in the colon.
A rupture in the colonic wall due to traumatic or pathologic processes.
Narrowing of the lumen of colon.
A circumscribed inflammatory and necrotic erosive lesion in the mucosa surface of the colon.
A disorder affecting the conduction system that sends electrical signals in the myocardium.
A heart disorder in which the pericardial sac becomes thickened and fibrotic, tightening the myocardium and impeding the normal myocardial function.
A laboratory test result which indicates increased levels of creatine phosphokinase in a biological specimen.
An infectious process affecting a cranial nerve.
A laboratory test result demonstrating an increased concentration of creatinine in a biological specimen.
A reemergence of renal cell carcinoma after a period of remission.
An inflammation of the bladder which is not caused by an infection of the urinary tract. Representative examples include interstitial cystitis and radiation-induced cystitis.

A syndrome that occurs after therapeutic infusion of antibodies into the blood and is characterized by nausea, headache, tachycardia, hypotension, rash, and shortness of breath. It is caused by the release of cytokines from the cells that are targeted by the antibodies. Most patients experience a mild to moderate reaction; however, the reaction may be severe and life-threatening.
Sexual dysfunction characterized by a delay in climax.
A neurologic state characterized by decreased ability to perceive and respond.
Any problem arising from the use of a medical device.
An infectious disorder caused by the use of a medical device.
An abnormal communication between the duodenum and another organ or cavity.
Bleeding originating from the duodenum.
An infectious process affecting the duodenum.
A rupture in the duodenal wall due to traumatic or pathologic processes.
A parathyroid gland carcinoma that has not spread to other anatomic sites.
Narrowing of the lumen of the duodenum.
An unusual sensation in the area of pharynx. It may be the initial manifestation of seizures associated with temporal lobe epilepsy.
Swelling due to an excessive accumulation of fluid in the upper or lower extremities.
Swelling due to an excessive accumulation of fluid in trunk area.
A disorder referring to problems related to ejaculation. This category includes premature, delayed, retrograde, and painful ejaculation.
An infectious process involving the endocardial layer of the heart.
An abnormal communication between the urinary bladder and the intestine.
Abnormally late fusion of the bone growth plate.
Abnormally early fusion of the bone growth plate.
A prescribed guide for conduct or action.
Leakage due to breakdown of an esophageal anastomosis.
Bleeding originating from the esophagus.

An agent that exerts a physiologic effect on neurotransmission or on any anatomic entity that is part of the nervous system, including the central nervous system (CNS) and peripheral nervous system (PNS).
An agent that exerts a physiologic effect on any anatomic entity that is part of the respiratory tract and airways.
An agent that exerts a physiologic effect on any anatomic entity that is part of the cardiovascular system, including the heart and blood vessels.

label.value: Agent Affecting Blood or Body Fluid

value.value: An agent that exerts an effect on the synthesis or function of blood, blood components or body fluids.

label.value: Agent Affecting Digestive System or Metabolism

value.value: An agent that exerts an effect on metabolism or any anatomic entity that is part of the gastrointestinal tract.
An infectious process affecting the esophagus.
A necrotic process involving the esophageal wall.
Blockage of the normal flow of the contents in the esophagus.
The reemergence of parathyroid gland carcinoma after a period of remission.
Painful sensation in the esophageal region.
Any agent that exerts an effect on muscle, bones and joints.
Bleeding from esophageal varices.
